# Intern Capstone — 4-Day Build

## Launchpad: the platform a company uses to turn a new hire into a settled employee

---

### The world you're building for

A growing company hires people faster than it can absorb them. Every new hire arrives to the same mess: a flurry of forms to sign, documents to hand over, accounts to set up, people to meet, and a manager who half-remembers what's supposed to happen in week one. HR chases everyone over email. Managers forget to approve things. New hires sit on their first day with no laptop and no idea what to do. Nobody can tell, at a glance, who's on track and who's stuck.

You're building **Launchpad** — the platform that runs onboarding from the moment someone accepts an offer until the day they're fully set up and productive. Over the next four days you'll build a working product that a real new hire, a real manager, and a real HR coordinator could all sign into and use to get a person onboarded without a single panicked email.

This document describes **what the product does**. It does not tell you how to build it — that's the assignment. Read it as a product spec, decide what the thing needs to be, and build it.

---

### The three kinds of people who use Launchpad

Everyone signs into their own account, and what they can see and do depends entirely on who they are. A person in one role should never be able to reach into another's world, even if they go looking.

**The New Hire** is the person being onboarded. They can:
- See their personal onboarding journey — a clear, ordered list of everything they need to do, with deadlines.
- Work through their tasks: read and acknowledge policies, fill in their details, and upload the documents they're asked for (signed offer, ID, tax and bank forms, certifications).
- Download the materials HR has prepared for them — the handbook, the org chart, their first-week schedule.
- Watch their own progress fill in as they complete things, and see what's still waiting on someone else.
- Lean on the Onboarding Buddy (described below) to make sense of it all.

**The Manager** owns the people on their team. They can:
- See the onboarding progress of *their own* new hires — and only theirs, never another manager's.
- Approve or send back the things that need a manager's sign-off (equipment requests, role-specific tasks).
- Add tasks specific to their team on top of the standard ones.
- See who's stuck and step in.

**The HR Coordinator** runs the whole program. They can:
- See every new hire across the company and the full state of everyone's onboarding.
- Design the standard onboarding journey and assign tasks to new hires.
- Review and approve the documents new hires upload (and reject one with a clear reason when something's wrong or missing).
- Watch the whole cohort update live and spot trouble before it becomes a problem.

These boundaries matter. A new hire who goes looking for another new hire's documents, or a manager who tries to peek at a different team's onboarding, must be cleanly and clearly turned away — never shown data that isn't theirs, never left at a crash or a blank page.

---

### The journey of a new hire

This is the heart of the product. Follow one person from offer to settled and you'll see most of what Launchpad has to do.

It begins when **HR adds a new hire and kicks off their journey**. The moment they do, the new hire gets a warm welcome email with a link to sign in and a clear sense of what's ahead. The manager is notified that one of their people is starting.

The **new hire signs in and works through their tasks**. Some are simple acknowledgements; some are forms that must be filled in correctly — and the forms should be hard to get wrong, telling the person exactly what's missing or malformed rather than rejecting them vaguely. Several tasks require uploading a document. When the new hire uploads their signed offer or their ID, it goes to HR for review; if HR sends it back, the new hire gets an email explaining precisely what to fix and the task reopens.

As the new hire ticks things off, **everyone watching sees their progress advance live** — HR's cohort view and the manager's team view both update the instant a task is completed, with no refresh. Tasks that need a manager's approval land in the manager's queue; when the manager approves, the new hire is notified and the journey moves forward.

Every document a new hire submits and every task they complete becomes part of their permanent record. Long after onboarding is over, HR can open that person's file and pull up the signed forms and certifications exactly as they were submitted.

When the last task is done, **onboarding completes**: the new hire gets a "you're all set" email, and the manager and HR see them cross the finish line on the board.

---

### The Onboarding Buddy

A new hire's first weeks are confusing, and Launchpad gives them an assistant they can talk to in plain language — the **Onboarding Buddy**. It's not a help page and it's not a bot that only talks; it actually *does things* on the new hire's behalf, and each new hire only ever sees their own.

A new hire should be able to type a real request and have the Buddy carry it out:

- **"What do I still need to do, and what's due first?"** — the Buddy looks at their journey and tells them exactly what's outstanding and by when.
- **"Request my laptop and book my orientation for Thursday."** — the Buddy actually submits the request and reserves the slot, the same way the new hire could by hand.
- **"Ask my manager when I'll get access to the team's systems."** — the Buddy drafts and sends a nudge to the right person on the new hire's behalf.

The Buddy should be genuinely useful — a confused new hire should be able to get unstuck through conversation alone. When it takes an action, that action shows up everywhere else in the product exactly as if the person had done it themselves.

---

### The board is alive

Launchpad is not a page people refresh. For HR and managers it's a live picture of every onboarding in flight.

When a new hire completes a task, the HR coordinator watching the cohort sees it update **on its own, the moment it happens**. If a manager approves something while HR has the board open, HR sees it change without touching anything. A nudge sent to a manager appears in their queue as it's sent. The new hire's own progress bar fills in live as they work.

If the product makes anyone hit refresh to find out what changed, it isn't finished.

---

### How the product should behave when things go wrong

A good product stays calm and clear when things get messy. Launchpad should:

- **Refuse what shouldn't be allowed, gracefully.** Reaching for someone else's record, or for something your role can't do, gets a clear, polite refusal — never someone else's data, never a crash.
- **Reject bad input helpfully.** Every form guards against nonsense and explains precisely what's wrong and how to fix it.
- **Explain the impossible.** When an action can't happen — approving a task that's already approved, completing onboarding with documents still rejected — the person gets a precise, human explanation, not a generic error.
- **Keep accounts and sign-in trustworthy.** People sign in securely and stay signed in sensibly, and their credentials are protected.

The difference between a demo and a product is almost entirely in how it behaves on the bad path. Spend real attention here.

---

### What "done" looks like

By the end of day four, someone should be able to:

1. Have HR add a new hire and trigger a welcome email with a working sign-in.
2. Sign in as that new hire, work through tasks, upload a document, and have it go to HR — who can approve it or send it back with a reason, triggering the right email either way.
3. Watch the manager's and HR's boards update live as the new hire makes progress, and have manager approvals flow back to the new hire.
4. Re-open that person's record weeks later and still pull up every document exactly as submitted.
5. Sit in the new hire's seat and get unstuck through the Onboarding Buddy — asking what's left, having it submit a request and book a slot, and having it nudge the manager.
6. Reach the end of the journey and have everyone see it complete, with a final email to the new hire.

If all six work end to end, and the product stays clear-headed when someone misuses it, you've built Launchpad.

---

### A suggested rhythm for the four days

This is guidance, not a rule — pace it however suits you.

- **Day 1** — Accounts and the three sign-in experiences; lock down the role boundaries early. Shape a new hire, a journey, and a task.
- **Day 2** — The full onboarding journey end to end: HR assigns → new hire completes tasks and uploads documents → HR/manager approve. Get the data and the role rules right first.
- **Day 3** — Make it live (cohort and team boards, progress, approvals updating in real time) and wire up the emails and the document uploads/records so everything persists.
- **Day 4** — Build the Onboarding Buddy and its three abilities, then harden the bad paths — refusals, validation, clear failures — and polish.

Build something you'd be comfortable handing to a real HR team on the morning a real new hire starts.
